<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<ecoSpold xmlns="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xsi:schemaLocation="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02 ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02.xsd http://www.EcoInvent.org/UsedUserMasterData ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02UserMasterData.xsd">
  <childActivityDataset>
    <activityDescription>
      <activity specialActivityType="0" id="c6421abb-07d2-527f-b42f-d0df99c92148" activityNameId="cfd006ce-d751-495c-b0e1-0a7191b4cbf1" parentActivityId="caa638f2-b11a-4c45-bd1d-d7f7fa2d147b" inheritanceDepth="-1" type="1" energyValues="0">
        <activityName xml:lang="en">p-nitrophenol production</activityName>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">C6H5NO3</synonym>
        <includedActivitiesStart xml:lang="en"/>
        <includedActivitiesEnd xml:lang="en">production of p-nitrophenol including materials, energy uses, infrastructure, and emissions</includedActivitiesEnd>
        <generalComment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">The process “p-nitrophenol, at plant, GLO" is modelled for the production of p-nitrophenol from phenol. Raw materials are modelled with a stoechiometric calculation. Emissions are estimated. Energy consumptions, infrastructure and transports are calculated with standard values.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">p-Nitrophenol (C6H5NO3; CAS 100-02-7, 4-nitrophenol, 1-hydroxy-4-nitrobenzene) forms yellow needles. The (metastable) α-form crystallizes from toluene above 63 °C, and the yellow, prismatic β-form crystallizes from toluene below 63 °C. 4-Nitrophenol is not steam volatile and is much more soluble in water (30 % at 100 °C) than the ortho isomer. Its flash point is 105 °C, and the decomposition point (explosive) of the sodium salt is 156 °C. 4-Chloronitrobenzene in 8.5 % sodium hydroxide solution is heated gradually (exothermic) to 170 °C in an autoclave and held there under pressure for 8 h. The resulting solution is cooled and acidified to give the product in 95 % yield.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">Another production route is nitration of phenol:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">C6H6O + HNO3 → C6H5NO3 + H2O</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4"></text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">Reduction of 4-nitrophenol to 4-aminophenol has largely been superseded by processes based on direct reduction of nitrobenzene. Reaction of sodium 4-nitrophenoxide with dialkylthiophosphoric chlorides (125 °C in chlorobenzene) gives a series of insecticides typified by parathion, which has largely been displaced by the less toxic methylparathion and related products. 4-Nitrophenol reacts with 4- chloro-3-nitrobenzotrifluoride to form fluorodifen; it is used as a herbicide specifically on drilled rice crops. </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="6">Frischknecht R., Jungbluth N., Althaus H.-J., Doka G., Dones R., Heck T., Hellweg S., Hischier R., Nemecek T., Rebitzer G. and Spielmann M. (2007) Overview and Methodology. Final report ecoinvent v2.0 No. 1. Swiss Centre for Life Cycle Inventories, Dübendorf, CH, retrieved from: www.ecoinvent.org.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="7"></text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="8">Gendorf (2000) Umwelterklärung 2000, Werk Gendorf. Werk Gendorf, Burgkirchen as pdf-File under: http://www.gendorf.de/pdf/umwelterklaerung2000.pdf</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="9"></text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="10">Kim 2003	Kim S., Overcash M.: Energy in chemical manufacturing processes: gate-to-gate information for life cycle assessment. In: Journal of Chemical Technology &amp; Biotechnology vol. 78,  no. 9: 995-1005(11). 2003</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="11"></text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="12">Gerald Booth: Nitro Compounds, Aromatic. Published online: 2003. In: Ullmann's Encyclopedia of Industrial Chemistry, Seventh Edition, 2004 Electronic Release (ed. Fiedler E., Grossmann G., Kersebohm D., Weiss G. and Witte C.). 7 th Electronic Release Edition. Wiley InterScience, New York, Online-Version under: DOI: 10.1002/14356007.a17_411</text>
        </generalComment>
      </activity>
